# Data Handling and Security

## Authentication & Authorization

- **Supabase Auth** for all authentication (email/password, OAuth providers)
- Server-side session validation on every protected route via `getUser()` (never trust client)
- **Row Level Security (RLS)** enabled on every table — no exceptions
- RLS policies follow least-privilege: users access only their own data unless explicitly shared

```sql
-- Example RLS policy
CREATE POLICY "Users can read own resumes"
  ON resumes FOR SELECT
  USING (auth.uid() = user_id);
```

## Input Validation

- **All user input** validated with Zod before processing — both client and server
- Sanitize file uploads: validate MIME type, file extension, and size (max 5MB for resumes)
- Accepted resume formats: `.pdf`, `.docx` only
- Parameterized queries only — Supabase client handles this, never concatenate SQL

## Data Privacy (GDPR-Aware)

- Collect only necessary data — no tracking beyond essential analytics
- Users can export their data (provide download endpoint)
- Users can delete their account and all associated data (cascade delete)
- Resume content stored in Supabase Storage with private buckets (signed URLs for access)
- PII fields identified and documented in schema comments

## Security Headers & Practices

- CSP, X-Frame-Options, X-Content-Type-Options configured in `next.config.js`
- HTTPS enforced (Vercel handles this by default)
- API rate limiting: implement via middleware (prepare for Upstash Redis on free tier)
- CSRF protection via SameSite cookies (Supabase Auth default)

## Secrets Management

```typescript
// src/config/env.ts — single source for all env vars
import { z } from "zod";

const envSchema = z.object({
  NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_URL: z.string().url(),
  NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_ANON_KEY: z.string().min(1),
  SUPABASE_SERVICE_ROLE_KEY: z.string().min(1),
});

export const env = envSchema.parse(process.env);
```

- Never commit `.env` files — use `.env.example` with placeholder values
- Server-only secrets never prefixed with `NEXT_PUBLIC_`
- Rotate keys immediately if exposed; use Supabase dashboard for key management

## Database Practices

- Enable `pgcrypto` extension for UUIDs as primary keys
- Timestamps: `created_at` (default `now()`) and `updated_at` (trigger-maintained) on every table
- Soft delete via `deleted_at` column for user-facing data (resumes, profiles)
- Foreign keys with appropriate `ON DELETE` behavior (CASCADE for owned data, RESTRICT for references)
- Index frequently queried columns (user_id, status, created_at)
